                            <comment id="105208" author="olivergierke" created="Wed, 2 Jul 2014 04:39:11 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Any chance you provide a tiny test case? What exactly does &quot;not work anymore&quot; mean? In 1.6.1 we shipped a fix for primitive version properties now considered &quot;new&quot; if they have the default value (0 for numbers usually). So your example domain type would&apos;ve been considered not new in 1.6 (which would&apos;ve triggered &lt;tt&gt;EntityManager.merge(&#8230;)&lt;/tt&gt; which is wrong) but should be considered new (and thus trigger &lt;tt&gt;EntityManager.persist(&#8230;)&lt;/tt&gt;).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Why does the test case expect an &lt;tt&gt;OptimisticLockException&lt;/tt&gt; at all?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="105209" author="olivergierke" created="Wed, 2 Jul 2014 04:43:52 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Editing the description of the ticket I just realized you&apos;re calling &lt;tt&gt;save(&#8230;)&lt;/tt&gt; twice. Why is this supposed to throw an &lt;tt&gt;OptimisticLockingException&lt;/tt&gt;? The first call considers the entity new, calls &lt;tt&gt;EntityManager.persist(&#8230;)&lt;/tt&gt; and thus updates the value of the version property to 1. The second call will see the updated value (hint: you &lt;b&gt;always&lt;/b&gt; should continue to work with the object returned by the &lt;tt&gt;save(&#8230;)&lt;/tt&gt; method as it is effectively allowed to return a completely new instance in some scenarios), and call &lt;tt&gt;EntityManager.merge(&#8230;)&lt;/tt&gt; which should work fine as the entity has exactly the version value expected.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="105231" author="vmonier108" created="Wed, 2 Jul 2014 08:17:00 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;agree, the test was just there to detect the difference between the 2 versions ofs spring-data-jpa.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;the following test works fine since &quot;version&quot; field is updated:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;MyEntity myEntity = new Entity();&lt;br/&gt;
myEntity.setId(&quot;myId&quot;);&lt;br/&gt;
assertEquals(0, myEntity.getVersion());&lt;br/&gt;
myEntity =    myEntityDao.save(myEntity);&lt;br/&gt;
assertEquals(1, myEntity.getVersion());&lt;br/&gt;
myEntity =     myEntityDao.save(myEntity);&lt;br/&gt;
assertEquals(2, myEntity.getVersion());&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This is why we try another &quot;dummy&quot; test to ensure the OptimisticLock occurs, since in the application this occurs randomly when 2 threads try to update the same data.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It looks like spring-data-jpa tries to persist the value without checking version value.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="105232" author="olivergierke" created="Wed, 2 Jul 2014 08:33:15 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Spring Data has never checked the version value (to throw an &lt;tt&gt;OptimisticLockingException&lt;/tt&gt;) and it never will. All we do is using the version property to differentiate between new (primitive version property with a value of 0 or a &lt;tt&gt;null&lt;/tt&gt; in a wrapper type such as &lt;tt&gt;Long&lt;/tt&gt;) and non-new entities (everything else).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&apos;d still love to see an executable test case that backs what you think doesn&apos;t work. So far we&apos;ve only seen code that&apos;s either invalid (the test case in the description) or working code (stuff in your last comment).&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="105275" author="vmonier108" created="Thu, 3 Jul 2014 04:30:08 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Archive contains a full maven based project with a JUnit test to reproduce the problem.&lt;br/&gt;
Change spring-data-jpa version in pom.xml file.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;My initial test was just an example and not sufficient. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This test is very close to what&apos;s happen in our application.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;With version 1.6.0.RELEASE the test throws an OptimisticLockException which is expected.&lt;br/&gt;
With version 1.6.1.RELEASE the test throws a DataIntegrityViolationException&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hope it will help&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="105280" author="olivergierke" created="Thu, 3 Jul 2014 06:18:09 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Thanks for that, I&apos;ll have a look.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
